Harsh Patil : General tell me the bhagavad gita sloka number 1.
Aira : The first sloka of the Bhagavad Gita is:
"dharmaḥ kṣetre kuru-kṣetre
samavetā yuyutsavaḥ
māmakāḥ pāṇḍavāś caiva
kim akurvata sañjaya"
(Bhagavad Gita, Chapter 1, Verse 1)
Harsh Patil : General tell me the meaning of that shlok.
Aira : The first sloka of the Bhagavad Gita translates to:
"Dharma (righteousness) is being destroyed in the land of Kuru (the battlefield), where the members of the Kuru clan and the Pandavas have gathered, eager for battle. What did they do, O Sanjaya?"
In essence, this verse sets the stage for the Bhagavad Gita, describing the scene of the great battle of Kurukshetra, where the Pandavas and the Kauravas are about to clash.
Harsh Patil : General most famous shlok from bhagavad gita.
Aira : One of the most famous and iconic slokas from the Bhagavad Gita is:
"karmany evadhikaras te
ma phalesu kadacana
ma karma-phala-hetur bhuh
ma te sango 'stv akarmani"
(Bhagavad Gita, Chapter 2, Verse 47)
Which translates to:
"You have a right to perform your prescribed duties, but you are not entitled to the fruits of your actions. Never consider yourself the cause of the results of your activities, and never be attached to not doing your duty."
This verse is often referred to as the core message of the Bhagavad Gita, emphasizing the importance of selfless action and detachment from the outcomes.